<section id="disparities-overview">
    <h2>The Reality of Cardiovascular Health Disparities</h2>

    <p>Heart disease is the leading cause of death across all racial and ethnic groups in America. But the burden is not equal. Structural inequities, healthcare access, and historical exclusion from research have created significant disparities that persist today.</p>

    <div class="warning-box">
        <h3>Key Disparity Statistics</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Black Americans</strong> are 30% more likely to die from heart disease than white Americans</li>
            <li><strong>South Asians</strong> have 2-4x higher heart disease rates, often 10 years earlier</li>
            <li><strong>Hispanic Americans</strong> are 20% more likely to have uncontrolled high blood pressure</li>
            <li><strong>Native Americans</strong> have the highest rates of heart disease of any ethnic group</li>
            <li><strong>Asian Americans</strong> are often misclassified as "low risk" despite varied risk profiles</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Why This Page Exists</h3>
    <p>For too long, cardiovascular medicine has been based primarily on research in white, middle-aged men. This has left entire communities without accurate information about their specific risks and optimal prevention strategies. This page aims to address that gap with evidence-based, culturally-informed information.</p>

    <div class="key-point">
        <h3>Important Context</h3>
        <p>Health disparities are not caused by race itself - they are caused by <strong>racism and systemic inequities</strong>. Race is a social construct, not a biological determinant of health. Disparities reflect differences in social determinants: healthcare access, economic opportunity, environmental factors, chronic stress, and historical injustice. Understanding this context is essential for addressing the true root causes.</p>
    </div>
</section>

<section id="african-american">
    <h2>African American Heart Health</h2>

    <p>Black Americans bear a disproportionate burden of cardiovascular disease, with higher rates of hypertension, stroke, heart failure, and sudden cardiac death compared to all other racial groups.</p>

    <div class="warning-box">
        <h3>Critical Statistics</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>56%</strong> of Black adults have hypertension (vs 48% white adults)</li>
            <li><strong>2x higher</strong> stroke death rate compared to white Americans</li>
            <li><strong>30% more likely</strong> to die from heart disease</li>
            <li><strong>60% higher</strong> rate of hypertension-related end-stage kidney disease</li>
            <li>Heart disease develops <strong>5-7 years earlier</strong> on average</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Key Risk Factors in Black Americans</h3>

    <h4>1. Hypertension: The Silent Killer</h4>
    <p>High blood pressure affects Black Americans at higher rates, earlier ages, and with more severe outcomes:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Develops earlier (often by age 35)</li>
        <li>More likely to be resistant to treatment</li>
        <li>Higher rates of end-organ damage (kidneys, heart, brain)</li>
        <li>May involve increased salt sensitivity</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>2. Diabetes and Insulin Resistance</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Black adults are <strong>60% more likely</strong> to be diagnosed with diabetes</li>
        <li>Higher rates of diabetic complications</li>
        <li>Often diagnosed at later, more advanced stages</li>
        <li>Metabolic syndrome rates significantly elevated</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>3. Obesity</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>49% of Black adults have obesity (vs 42% overall US rate)</li>
        <li>Black women have highest obesity rates of any demographic</li>
        <li>Body composition and metabolic impact may differ from other groups</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>The Stress Factor: Weathering</h3>
    <p>Dr. Arline Geronimus's "weathering hypothesis" describes how chronic stress from discrimination accelerates biological aging and disease:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Elevated cortisol from chronic stress</li>
        <li>Inflammatory markers persistently elevated</li>
        <li>Telomere shortening (cellular aging)</li>
        <li>"Allostatic load" - wear and tear on body systems</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="key-point">
        <h3>The Jackson Heart Study</h3>
        <p>The Jackson Heart Study is the largest study of cardiovascular disease in African Americans, following over 5,000 participants in Jackson, Mississippi. Key findings include:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Discrimination is associated with higher blood pressure</li>
            <li>John Henryism (high-effort coping) linked to cardiovascular strain</li>
            <li>Social support is protective against heart disease</li>
            <li>Access to healthy food environments matters significantly</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
</section>

<section id="hispanic-latino">
    <h2>Hispanic/Latino Heart Health</h2>

    <p>The Hispanic/Latino population is diverse, with cardiovascular risk varying significantly by heritage and acculturation level. The "Hispanic Paradox" - where Hispanic Americans have lower mortality despite higher poverty rates - is now being reconsidered as data becomes more nuanced.</p>

    <div class="key-point">
        <h3>Key Statistics</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>1 in 3</strong> Hispanic adults has high blood pressure</li>
            <li><strong>17%</strong> of Hispanic adults have diabetes (vs 8% non-Hispanic whites)</li>
            <li><strong>20% more likely</strong> to have uncontrolled hypertension</li>
            <li>Mexican Americans have <strong>higher rates</strong> of metabolic syndrome</li>
            <li>Heart disease rates <strong>increase with acculturation</strong></li>
        </ul>
    </div>

