    <h3>Acculturation and Heart Disease</h3>
    <p>Studies consistently show that heart disease risk <strong>increases</strong> with time living in the United States:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Dietary patterns shift toward processed foods</li>
        <li>Physical activity often decreases</li>
        <li>Stress from discrimination and economic pressures</li>
        <li>Loss of protective cultural and family structures</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section id="south-asian">
    <h2>South Asian Heart Health</h2>

    <p>People of South Asian descent (ancestry from India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, Nepal, Bhutan) face the <strong>highest rates of cardiovascular disease</strong> of any ethnic group worldwide - often developing disease 10 years earlier than other populations.</p>

    <div class="warning-box">
        <h3>Critical Statistics</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>2-4x higher</strong> risk of coronary heart disease compared to European ancestry</li>
            <li>Heart attacks occur <strong>10 years earlier</strong> on average</li>
            <li><strong>50%</strong> of heart attacks occur under age 50 in South Asians</li>
            <li><strong>25%</strong> of South Asian adults have diabetes or pre-diabetes</li>
            <li>Heart disease is the <strong>#1 cause of death</strong> among South Asians globally</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>The South Asian Paradox</h3>
    <p>South Asians develop heart disease at "normal" or even low BMI levels. This has led to recognition that standard BMI cutoffs don't apply:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>BMI 23</strong> (not 25) should be considered overweight for South Asians</li>
        <li><strong>BMI 27.5</strong> (not 30) should be considered obese</li>
        <li>Central obesity (waist circumference) is more predictive than BMI</li>
        <li>Even "thin" South Asians may have high visceral fat</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Key Risk Factors Unique to South Asians</h3>

    <h4>1. Insulin Resistance & Metabolic Syndrome</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Higher rates even at lower body weights</li>
        <li>Genetic predisposition to insulin resistance</li>
        <li>"Thin-fat phenotype" - normal weight with high body fat percentage</li>
        <li>Metabolic syndrome rates 3x higher than white populations</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>2. Elevated Lipoprotein(a)</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Lp(a) is an independent genetic risk factor</li>
        <li>South Asians have higher Lp(a) levels on average</li>
        <li>Not affected by lifestyle - genetically determined</li>
        <li>Increases risk of early heart disease and stroke</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>3. Atherogenic Dyslipidemia</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Higher triglycerides</li>
        <li>Lower HDL cholesterol</li>
        <li>More small, dense LDL particles</li>
        <li>This pattern promotes atherosclerosis</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="key-point">
        <h3>The MASALA Study</h3>
        <p>The Mediators of Atherosclerosis in South Asians Living in America (MASALA) study is providing crucial data on South Asian cardiovascular health. Key findings:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>46% of South Asian Americans have metabolic syndrome</li>
            <li>High rates of fatty liver disease</li>
            <li>Coronary artery calcification common even in young adults</li>
            <li>Traditional risk calculators underestimate South Asian risk</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Dietary Considerations</h3>
    <p>Traditional South Asian diets have evolved, and modern eating patterns contribute to risk:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Refined carbohydrates:</strong> White rice, naan, processed foods</li>
        <li><strong>Cooking oils:</strong> Some traditional ghee use is fine; avoid refined vegetable oils</li>
        <li><strong>Sugar:</strong> High consumption in chai, sweets, traditional desserts</li>
        <li><strong>Frequency of eating:</strong> Multiple meals and snacks keep insulin elevated</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section id="native-american">
    <h2>Native American/Alaska Native Heart Health</h2>

    <p>American Indian and Alaska Native (AI/AN) populations have the <strong>highest rates of heart disease</strong> of any ethnic group in the United States, with death rates 50% higher than for white Americans.</p>

    <div class="warning-box">
        <h3>Critical Statistics</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>50% higher</strong> heart disease death rate compared to white Americans</li>
            <li><strong>2.5x higher</strong> diabetes rate than general population</li>
            <li>Heart disease is leading cause of death for AI/AN people</li>
            <li><strong>36%</strong> have high blood pressure</li>
            <li>Life expectancy <strong>5.5 years shorter</strong> than US average</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>The Strong Heart Study</h3>
    <p>The Strong Heart Study is the largest study of cardiovascular disease in American Indians, following over 4,500 participants from 13 tribes. Key findings:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Diabetes is the dominant risk factor in AI/AN cardiovascular disease</li>
        <li>Obesity rates among the highest in the world</li>
        <li>Higher rates of heart failure compared to other populations</li>
        <li>Traditional lifestyle factors (when maintained) are protective</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Historical and Structural Factors</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Food sovereignty loss:</strong> Forced dietary changes from traditional foods</li>
        <li><strong>Healthcare access:</strong> Indian Health Service chronically underfunded</li>
        <li><strong>Food deserts:</strong> Many reservations lack access to fresh food</li>
        <li><strong>Historical trauma:</strong> Intergenerational effects of colonization</li>
        <li><strong>Geographic isolation:</strong> Limited access to specialists and emergency care</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="key-point">
        <h3>Traditional Foods as Medicine</h3>
        <p>Research shows that returning to traditional food systems improves health outcomes. Traditional Native American foods - wild game, fish, indigenous plants, traditional preparation methods - align with metabolic health principles: low in processed carbohydrates, high in protein and healthy fats, eaten in seasonal patterns that naturally incorporate fasting.</p>
    </div>
</section>

