<section id="root-causes">
    <h2>Root Causes of Health Disparities</h2>

    <p>Understanding why disparities exist is essential for addressing them. The causes are systemic, not biological:</p>

    <h3>Social Determinants of Health</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Healthcare access:</strong> Insurance coverage, provider availability, language barriers</li>
        <li><strong>Economic factors:</strong> Income, employment, housing stability</li>
        <li><strong>Education:</strong> Health literacy, access to information</li>
        <li><strong>Environment:</strong> Food deserts, pollution, neighborhood safety</li>
        <li><strong>Social context:</strong> Discrimination, chronic stress, social support</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Healthcare System Failures</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Implicit bias:</strong> Studies show providers often treat minority patients differently</li>
        <li><strong>Communication gaps:</strong> Cultural and linguistic barriers</li>
        <li><strong>Treatment disparities:</strong> Minorities less likely to receive optimal interventions</li>
        <li><strong>Research exclusion:</strong> Underrepresentation in clinical trials</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Historical Exclusion from Research</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Pre-1993:</strong> Minorities largely excluded from clinical trials</li>
        <li><strong>Tuskegee legacy:</strong> Historical medical abuse creates justified distrust</li>
        <li><strong>Current gaps:</strong> African Americans are only 5% of clinical trial participants</li>
        <li><strong>Result:</strong> Treatments may not be optimal for diverse populations</li>
    </ul>
</section>

