<section id="prevention">
    <h2>Culturally-Informed Prevention Strategies</h2>

    <h3>Universal Prevention Principles</h3>
    <p>Regardless of ethnicity, these evidence-based principles apply:</p>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>Address insulin resistance</strong> - The root cause in most populations</li>
        <li><strong>Get proper testing</strong> - Blood pressure, fasting insulin, coronary calcium score</li>
        <li><strong>Implement time-restricted eating</strong> - Reduces insulin, inflammation</li>
        <li><strong>Prioritize sleep</strong> - 7-8 hours minimum</li>
        <li><strong>Manage stress</strong> - Chronic stress drives disease</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>Adapting Prevention to Cultural Context</h3>

    <div class="key-point">
        <h3>Dietary Adaptations</h3>
        <p>Rather than abandoning cultural foods, modify them for metabolic health:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Traditional foods are often healthier</strong> than Western processed alternatives</li>
            <li><strong>Reduce refined carbohydrates:</strong> White rice, naan, tortillas from refined flour</li>
            <li><strong>Keep traditional proteins:</strong> Fish, legumes, eggs, traditional meats</li>
            <li><strong>Increase vegetables:</strong> Traditional preparations often include abundant vegetables</li>
            <li><strong>Mind cooking oils:</strong> Traditional fats (ghee, lard in moderation) may be better than industrial seed oils</li>
            <li><strong>Reduce sugar:</strong> Sweet tea, traditional desserts, added sugars in cooking</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Population-Specific Recommendations</h3>

    <h4>For Black Americans</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Blood pressure monitoring is critical - check regularly</li>
        <li>Be aware of salt sensitivity - reduce sodium intake</li>
        <li>Advocate for appropriate medication choices (some BP meds work better in Black patients)</li>
        <li>Address chronic stress - discrimination takes a physical toll</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>For South Asians</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Get tested early - don't assume "normal" BMI means low risk</li>
        <li>Request Lp(a) testing - this genetic marker is often elevated</li>
        <li>Use modified BMI thresholds (overweight at 23, not 25)</li>
        <li>Reduce refined carbs even if you're not overweight</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>For Hispanic/Latino Communities</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Monitor for diabetes carefully - high risk population</li>
        <li>Traditional foods from before processed foods became common were protective</li>
        <li>Be aware that risk increases with acculturation to Western diet</li>
        <li>Language-accessible healthcare resources matter</li>
    </ul>
</section>

