    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Are South Asians at higher risk for heart disease?</h3>
        <p>Yes, significantly. South Asians (those with ancestry from India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, Nepal) have 2-4x higher rates of heart disease compared to other ethnic groups, often occurring 10 years earlier. This is linked to higher rates of insulin resistance, central obesity, elevated lipoprotein(a), and metabolic syndrome - even at "normal" BMI levels.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Why is heart disease research lacking for minorities?</h3>
        <p>Until 1993, minorities were largely excluded from clinical research. Even today, African Americans make up only 5% of clinical trial participants despite being 13% of the population. This means treatments and guidelines are often based on data from white patients and may not be optimal for other groups. Recent initiatives like the ARIC study and Jackson Heart Study are working to address this gap.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How can communities of color reduce heart disease risk?</h3>
        <p>Evidence-based prevention includes: getting proper screening (blood pressure, fasting insulin, coronary calcium score), addressing insulin resistance through diet and fasting protocols, managing stress and sleep, finding culturally competent healthcare providers, advocating for yourself in medical settings, and building community support. Prevention strategies should be adapted to cultural food traditions while maintaining metabolic health principles.</p>
